# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: average-case-complexity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In computational complexity theory, the **average-case complexity** of an algorithm is the amount of some computational resource (typically time) used by the algorithm, averaged over all possible inputs.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] It is frequently contrasted with worst-case complexity which considers the maximal complexity of the algorithm over all possible inputs.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] There are three primary motivations for studying average-case complexity.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] First, although some problems may be intractable in the worst-case, the inputs which elicit this behavior may rarely occur in practice, so the average-case complexity may be a more accurate measure of an algorithm's performance.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Second, average-case complexity analysis provides tools and techniques to generate hard instances of problems which can be utilized in areas such as cryptography and derandomization.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Third, average-case complexity allows discriminating the most efficient algorithm in practice among algorithms of equivalent best case complexity (for instance Quicksort).
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Average-case analysis requires a notion of an "average" input to an algorithm, which leads to the problem of devising a probability distribution over inputs.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Alternatively, a randomized algorithm can be used.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The analysis of such algorithms leads to the related notion of an **expected complexity**.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The average-case performance of algorithms has been studied since modern notions of computational efficiency were developed in the 1950s.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Much of this initial work focused on problems for which worst-case polynomial time algorithms were already known.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In 1973, Donald Knuth published Volume 3 of the Art of Computer Programming which extensively surveys average-case performance of algorithms for problems solvable in worst-case polynomial time, such as sorting and median-finding.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] An efficient algorithm for **NP**-complete problems is generally characterized as one which runs in polynomial time for all inputs; this is equivalent to requiring efficient worst-case complexity.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] However, an algorithm which is inefficient on a "small" number of inputs may still be efficient for "most" inputs that occur in practice.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Thus, it is desirable to study the properties of these algorithms where the average-case complexity may differ from the worst-case complexity and find methods to relate the two.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The fundamental notions of average-case complexity were developed by Leonid Levin in 1986 when he published a one-page paper defining average-case complexity and completeness while giving an example of a complete problem for **distNP**, the average-case analogue of **NP**.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The first task is to precisely define what is meant by an algorithm which is efficient "on average".
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] An initial attempt might define an efficient average-case algorithm as one which runs in expected polynomial time over all possible inputs.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Such a definition has various shortcomings; in particular, it is not robust to changes in the computational model.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] For example, suppose algorithm A runs in time *t**A*(*x*) on input x and algorithm B runs in time *t**A*(*x*)2 on input x; that is, B is quadratically slower than A.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Intuitively, any definition of average-case efficiency should capture the idea that A is efficient-on-average if and only if B is efficient on-average.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Suppose, however, that the inputs are drawn randomly from the uniform distribution of strings with length n, and that A runs in time *n*2 on all inputs except the string 1*n* for which A takes time 2*n*.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Then it can be easily checked that the expected running time of A is polynomial but the expected running time of B is exponential.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] To create a more robust definition of average-case efficiency, it makes sense to allow an algorithm A to run longer than polynomial time on some inputs but the fraction of inputs on which A requires larger and larger running time becomes smaller and smaller.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] for every *n*, *t* > 0 and polynomial p, where *t**A*(*x*) denotes the running time of algorithm A on input x, and ε is a positive constant value.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] for some constants C and ε, where *n* = |*x*|.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In other words, an algorithm A has good average-case complexity if, after running for *t**A*(*n*) steps, A can solve all but a ⁠*n**c*/(*t**A*(*n*))*ε*⁠ fraction of inputs of length n, for some *ε*, *c* > 0.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The next step is to define the "average" input to a particular problem.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] This is achieved by associating the inputs of each problem with a particular probability distribution.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] That is, an "average-case" problem consists of a language L and an associated probability distribution D which forms the pair (*L*, *D*).
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Polynomial-time samplable distributions (**P**-samplable): these are distributions from which it is possible to draw random samples in polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] These two formulations, while similar, are not equivalent.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] If a distribution is **P**-computable it is also **P**-samplable, but the converse is not true if **P** ≠ **P****#P**.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] A distributional problem (*L*, *D*) is in the complexity class **AvgP** if there is an efficient average-case algorithm for L, as defined above.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The class **AvgP** is occasionally called **distP** in the literature.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] A distributional problem (*L*, *D*) is in the complexity class **distNP** if L is in **NP** and D is **P**-computable.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] When L is in **NP** and D is **P**-samplable, (*L*, *D*) belongs to **sampNP**.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Together, **AvgP** and **distNP** define the average-case analogues of **P** and **NP**, respectively.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Let (*L*,*D*) and (*L′*, *D′*) be two distributional problems.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The domination condition enforces the notion that if problem (*L*, *D*) is hard on average, then (*L′*, *D′*) is also hard on average.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Intuitively, a reduction should provide a way to solve an instance x of problem L by computing *f*(*x*) and feeding the output to the algorithm which solves L'.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The domination condition only allows such strings to occur polynomially as often in D'.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The average-case analogue to **NP**-completeness is **distNP**-completeness.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In his original paper, Levin showed an example of a distributional tiling problem that is average-case **NP**-complete.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] A survey of known **distNP**-complete problems is available online.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] One area of active research involves finding new **distNP**-complete problems.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] However, finding such problems can be complicated due to a result of Gurevich which shows that any distributional problem with a flat distribution cannot be **distNP**-complete unless **EXP** = **NEXP**.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] (A flat distribution μ is one for which there exists an *ε* > 0 such that for any x, *μ*(*x*) ≤ 2−|*x*|*ε*.) A result by Livne shows that all natural **NP**-complete problems have **DistNP**-complete versions.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] However, the goal of finding a natural distributional problem that is **DistNP**-complete has not yet been achieved.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] As mentioned above, much early work relating to average-case complexity focused on problems for which polynomial-time algorithms already existed, such as sorting.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] For example, many sorting algorithms which utilize randomness, such as Quicksort, have a worst-case running time of O(*n*2), but an average-case running time of O(*n* log(*n*)), where n is the length of the input to be sorted.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] For most problems, average-case complexity analysis is undertaken to find efficient algorithms for a problem that is considered difficult in the worst-case.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In cryptographic applications, however, the opposite is true: the worst-case complexity is irrelevant; we instead want a guarantee that the average-case complexity of every algorithm which "breaks" the cryptographic scheme is inefficient.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Thus, all secure cryptographic schemes rely on the existence of one-way functions.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Although the existence of one-way functions is still an open problem, many candidate one-way functions are based on hard problems such as integer factorization or computing the discrete log.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In fact, both the integer factorization and discrete log problems are in **NP** ∩ **coNP**, and are therefore not believed to be **NP**-complete.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] The fact that all of cryptography is predicated on the existence of average-case intractable problems in **NP** is one of the primary motivations for studying average-case complexity.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In 1990, Impagliazzo and Levin showed that if there is an efficient average-case algorithm for a **distNP**-complete problem under the uniform distribution, then there is an average-case algorithm for every problem in **NP** under any polynomial-time samplable distribution.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Applying this theory to natural distributional problems remains an outstanding open question.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In 1992, Ben-David et al. showed that if all languages in **distNP** have good-on-average decision algorithms, they also have good-on-average search algorithms.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Further, they show that this conclusion holds under a weaker assumption: if every language in **NP** is easy on average for decision algorithms with respect to the uniform distribution, then it is also easy on average for search algorithms with respect to the uniform distribution.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] Thus, cryptographic one-way functions can exist only if there are **distNP** problems over the uniform distribution that are hard on average for decision algorithms.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] In 2003, Bogdanov and Trevisan generalized this result to arbitrary non-adaptive reductions.
[src:average-case-complexity/average-case-complexity] These results show that it is unlikely that any association can be made between average-case complexity and worst-case complexity via reductions.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] In computer science, **best**, **worst**, and **average cases** of a given algorithm express what the resource usage is *at least*, *at most* and *on average*, respectively.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Usually the resource being considered is running time, i.e. time complexity, but could also be memory or some other resource.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Best case is the function which performs the minimum number of steps on input data of n elements.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Worst case is the function which performs the maximum number of steps on input data of size n.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Average case is the function which performs an average number of steps on input data of n elements.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] In real-time computing, the worst-case execution time is often of particular concern since it is important to know how much time might be needed *in the worst case* to guarantee that the algorithm will always finish on time.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Average performance and worst-case performance are the most used in algorithm analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Less widely found is best-case performance, but it does have uses: for example, where the best cases of individual tasks are known, they can be used to improve the accuracy of an overall worst-case analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Computer scientists use probabilistic analysis techniques, especially expected value, to determine expected running times.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] The terms are used in other contexts; for example the worst- and best-case outcome of an epidemic, worst-case temperature to which an electronic circuit element is exposed, etc.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Where components of specified tolerance are used, devices must be designed to work properly with the worst-case combination of tolerances and external conditions.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] The term *best-case performance* is used in computer science to describe an algorithm's behavior under optimal conditions.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] For example, the best case for a simple linear search on a list occurs when the desired element is the first element of the list.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Development and choice of algorithms is rarely based on best-case performance: most academic and commercial enterprises are more interested in improving average-case complexity and worst-case performance.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Algorithms may also be trivially modified to have good best-case running time by hard-coding solutions to a finite set of inputs, making the measure almost meaningless.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Worst-case performance analysis and average-case performance analysis have some similarities, but in practice usually require different tools and approaches.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Determining what *typical input* means is difficult, and often that average input has properties which make it difficult to characterise mathematically (consider, for instance, algorithms that are designed to operate on strings of text).
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Similarly, even when a sensible description of a particular "average case" (which will probably only be applicable for some uses of the algorithm) is possible, they tend to result in more difficult analysis of equations.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Worst-case analysis gives a *safe* analysis (the worst case is never underestimated), but one which can be overly *pessimistic*, since there may be no (realistic) input that would take this many steps.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] In some situations it may be necessary to use a pessimistic analysis in order to guarantee safety.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Often however, a pessimistic analysis may be too pessimistic, so an analysis that gets closer to the real value but may be optimistic (perhaps with some known low probability of failure) can be a much more practical approach.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] One modern approach in academic theory to bridge the gap between worst-case and average-case analysis is called smoothed analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] When analyzing algorithms which often take a small time to complete, but periodically require a much larger time, amortized analysis can be used to determine the worst-case running time over a (possibly infinite) series of operations.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] This **amortized** cost can be much closer to the average cost, while still providing a guaranteed upper limit on the running time.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] So e.g. online algorithms are frequently based on amortized analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] The worst-case analysis is related to the worst-case complexity.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Many algorithms with bad worst-case performance have good average-case performance.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] For problems we want to solve, this is a good thing: we can hope that the particular instances we care about are average.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] For cryptography, this is very bad: we want typical instances of a cryptographic problem to be hard.
[src:average-case-complexity/best-worst-and-average-case] Here methods like random self-reducibility can be used for some specific problems to show that the worst case is no harder than the average case, or, equivalently, that the average case is no easier than the worst case.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] In computational complexity theory, **NP-complete** problems are the hardest of the problems to which *solutions* can be verified *quickly*.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Each input to the problem is associated with a collection of short (polynomial length) *solutions*, which might or might not validly solve the input.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The output is "yes" when at least one of these solutions is valid, and "no" when none of them are.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The validity of each solution can be verified quickly (namely, in polynomial time), and a brute-force search algorithm can find a valid solution (if one exists) by trying all possible solutions.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The problem can be used to simulate every other problem for which we can verify quickly that a solution is valid.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Hence, if we could find valid solutions of some NP-complete problem quickly (when they exist), we could quickly find valid solutions for every other problem in which a given solution can be easily verified.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Problems that meet the first three criteria belong to the class NP, which is short for "nondeterministic polynomial-time".
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] In this name, "nondeterministic" refers to nondeterministic Turing machines, a way of mathematically formalizing the idea of a brute-force search algorithm.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Polynomial time refers to an amount of time that is considered "quick" for a deterministic algorithm to check a single solution, or for a nondeterministic Turing machine to perform the whole search.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] A problem that is in NP and also meets the fourth criterion is said to be "NP-complete".
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The term "complete" refers to the property of being able to simulate everything in the same complexity class: If some NP-complete problem has a polynomial time algorithm, all problems in NP do.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The set of NP-complete problems is often denoted by **NP-C** or **NPC**.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Although a solution to an NP-complete problem can be *verified* "quickly", there is no known way to *find* a solution quickly.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] That is, the time required to solve the problem using any currently known algorithm increases rapidly as the size of the problem grows.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] As a consequence, determining whether it is possible to solve these problems quickly, called the P versus NP problem, is one of the fundamental unsolved problems in computer science today.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] While a method for computing the solutions to NP-complete problems quickly remains undiscovered, computer scientists and programmers still frequently encounter NP-complete problems.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] NP-complete problems are often addressed by using heuristic methods and approximation algorithms.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Every problem in NP is reducible to $\scriptstyle C$ in polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] $\scriptstyle C$ can be shown to be in NP by demonstrating that a candidate solution to $\scriptstyle C$ can be verified in polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] A decision problem that is solvable in polynomial time belongs to the class P.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] All problems in P are necessarily in NP.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] However, it has not been proved that the class NP is actually larger than P.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] In other words, it is not yet known whether there exist problems in NP that are not in P.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The question of whether the classes P and NP are equal or not is known as the P versus NP problem.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] A consequence of the definition of NP-completeness is that if we had a polynomial time algorithm (on a UTM, or any other Turing-equivalent abstract machine) for $\scriptstyle C$ , we could solve all problems in NP in polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] A problem is said to be NP-hard if everything in NP can be transformed in polynomial time into it even though it may not be in NP.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] A problem is NP-complete if it is both in NP and NP-hard.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The NP-complete problems are thus, in a sense, the hardest problems in NP.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The Cook–Levin theorem states that the Boolean satisfiability problem is NP-complete, establishing for the first time that such problems do exist.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] In 1972, Richard Karp proved that several other problems were also NP-complete (see Karp's 21 NP-complete problems); thus, there is a class of NP-complete problems, besides Boolean satisfiability.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Since these original results, thousands of other problems have been shown to be NP-complete by reductions from other problems previously shown to be NP-complete; many of these problems are collected in Garey & Johnson (1979).
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The easiest way to prove that some new problem is NP-complete is first to prove that it is in NP, and then to reduce some known NP-complete problem to it.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Therefore, it is useful to know a variety of NP-complete problems.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The list below contains some well-known problems that are NP-complete when expressed as decision problems.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] To the right is a diagram of some of the problems and the reductions typically used to prove their NP-completeness.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] In this diagram, problems are reduced from bottom to top.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Note that this diagram is misleading as a description of the mathematical relationship between these problems, as there exists a polynomial-time reduction between any two NP-complete problems; but it indicates where demonstrating this polynomial-time reduction has been easiest.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] There is often only a small difference between a problem in P and an NP-complete problem.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] For example, the 3-satisfiability problem, a restriction of the Boolean satisfiability problem, remains NP-complete, whereas the slightly more restricted 2-satisfiability problem is in P (specifically, it is NL-complete), but the slightly more general max.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Determining whether a graph can be colored with 2 colors is in P, but with 3 colors is NP-complete, even when restricted to planar graphs.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Determining if a graph is a cycle or is bipartite is very easy (in L), but finding a maximum bipartite or a maximum cycle subgraph is NP-complete.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] A solution of the knapsack problem within any fixed percentage of the optimal solution can be computed in polynomial time, but finding the optimal solution is NP-complete.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] An interesting example is the graph isomorphism problem, the graph theory problem of determining whether a graph isomorphism exists between two graphs.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Two graphs are isomorphic if one can be transformed into the other simply by renaming vertices.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The Subgraph Isomorphism problem is NP-complete.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The graph isomorphism problem is suspected to be neither in P nor NP-complete, though it is in NP.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] This is an example of a problem that is thought to be *hard*, but is not thought to be NP-complete.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] This class is called NP-Intermediate problems and exists if and only if P≠NP.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] At present, all known algorithms for NP-complete problems require time that is superpolynomial in the input size.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] In the definition of NP-complete given above, the term *reduction* was used in the technical meaning of a polynomial-time many-one reduction.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Another type of reduction is polynomial-time Turing reduction.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] A problem $\scriptstyle X$ is polynomial-time Turing-reducible to a problem $\scriptstyle Y$ if, given a subroutine that solves $\scriptstyle Y$ in polynomial time, one could write a program that calls this subroutine and solves $\scriptstyle X$ in polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] This contrasts with many-one reducibility, which has the restriction that the program can only call the subroutine once, and the return value of the subroutine must be the return value of the program.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] If one defines the analogue to NP-complete with Turing reductions instead of many-one reductions, the resulting set of problems won't be smaller than NP-complete; it is an open question whether it will be any larger.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Another type of reduction that is also often used to define NP-completeness is the logarithmic-space many-one reduction which is a many-one reduction that can be computed with only a logarithmic amount of space.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Since every computation that can be done in logarithmic space can also be done in polynomial time it follows that if there is a logarithmic-space many-one reduction then there is also a polynomial-time many-one reduction.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] This type of reduction is more refined than the more usual polynomial-time many-one reductions and it allows us to distinguish more classes such as P-complete.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Whether under these types of reductions the definition of NP-complete changes is still an open problem.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] All currently known NP-complete problems are NP-complete under log space reductions.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] All currently known NP-complete problems remain NP-complete even under much weaker reductions such as $AC_{0}$ reductions and $NC_{0}$ reductions.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] Some NP-Complete problems such as SAT are known to be complete even under polylogarithmic time projections.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] It is known, however, that AC0 reductions define a strictly smaller class than polynomial-time reductions.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The concept of NP-completeness was introduced in 1971 (see Cook–Levin theorem), though the term *NP-complete* was introduced later.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] At the 1971 STOC conference, there was a fierce debate between the computer scientists about whether NP-complete problems could be solved in polynomial time on a deterministic Turing machine.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] John Hopcroft brought everyone at the conference to a consensus that the question of whether NP-complete problems are solvable in polynomial time should be put off to be solved at some later date, since nobody had any formal proofs for their claims one way or the other.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The Clay Mathematics Institute named the P versus NP question one of the seven Millennium Prize Problems in 2000.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] According to Donald Knuth, the name "NP-complete" was popularized by Alfred Aho, John Hopcroft and Jeffrey Ullman in their celebrated textbook "The Design and Analysis of Computer Algorithms".
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] He reports that they introduced the change in the galley proofs for the book (from "polynomially-complete"), in accordance with the results of a poll he had conducted of the theoretical computer science community.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] The following misconceptions are frequent.
[src:average-case-complexity/np-completeness] It is not known whether NPC is closed under complementation, since NPC=co-NPC if and only if NP=co-NP, and since NP=co-NP is an open question.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] In computer science, a **one-way function** is a function that is easy to compute on every input, but hard to invert given the image of a random input.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Here, "easy" and "hard" are to be understood in the sense of computational complexity theory, specifically the theory of polynomial time problems.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] This has nothing to do with whether the function is one-to-one; finding any one input with the desired image is considered a successful inversion.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The existence of such one-way functions is still an open conjecture.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Their existence would prove that the complexity classes P and NP are not equal, thus resolving the foremost unsolved question of theoretical computer science.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The converse is not known to be true, i.e. the existence of a proof that P ≠ NP would not directly imply the existence of one-way functions.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] In applied contexts, the terms "easy" and "hard" are usually interpreted relative to some specific computing entity; typically "cheap enough for the legitimate users" and "prohibitively expensive for any malicious agents".
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] One-way functions, in this sense, are fundamental tools for cryptography, personal identification, authentication, and other data security applications.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] While the existence of one-way functions in this sense is also an open conjecture, there are several candidates that have withstood decades of intense scrutiny.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Some of them are essential ingredients of most telecommunications, e-commerce, and e-banking systems around the world.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] A function *f* : {0, 1}* → {0, 1}* is **one-way** if *f* can be computed by a polynomial-time algorithm, but any polynomial-time randomized algorithm F that attempts to compute a pseudo-inverse for *f* succeeds with negligible probability.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] where the probability is over the choice of *x* from the discrete uniform distribution on {0, 1} *n*, and the randomness of F .
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Note that, by this definition, the function must be "hard to invert" in the average-case, rather than worst-case sense.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] This is different from much of complexity theory (e.g., NP-hardness), where the term "hard" is meant in the worst-case.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] That is why even if some candidates for one-way functions (described below) are known to be NP-complete, it does not imply their one-wayness.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The latter property is only based on the lack of known algorithms to solve the problem.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] It is not sufficient to make a function "lossy" (not one-to-one) to have a one-way function.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] In particular, the function that outputs the string of *n* zeros on any input of length *n* is *not* a one-way function because it is easy to come up with an input that will result in the same output.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] More precisely: For such a function that simply outputs a string of zeroes, an algorithm *F* that just outputs any string of length *n* on input *f*(*x*) will "find" a proper preimage of the output, even if it is not the input which was originally used to find the output string.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] A **one-way permutation** is a one-way function that is also a permutation—that is, a one-way function that is bijective.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] One-way permutations are an important cryptographic primitive, and it is not known if their existence is implied by the existence of one-way functions.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] A trapdoor one-way function or trapdoor permutation is a special kind of one-way function.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Such a function is hard to invert unless some secret information, called the *trapdoor*, is known.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] A **collision-free hash function** *f* is a one-way function that is also *collision-resistant*; that is, no randomized polynomial time algorithm can find a collision—distinct values *x*, *y* such that *f*(*x*) = *f*(*y*)—with non-negligible probability.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] A hard-core predicate of a one-way function *f* is a predicate (i.e. single bit) *b* such that *b(x)* is easy to compute given *x* but hard to compute given only *f(x)*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] If *f* is a one-way function, then the inversion of *f* would be a problem whose output is hard to compute (by definition) but easy to check (just by computing *f* on it).
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Thus, the existence of a one-way function implies that FP ≠ FNP, which in turn implies that P ≠ NP.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] However, P ≠ NP does not imply the existence of one-way functions.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The following are several candidates for one-way functions (as of April 2009).
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Clearly, it is not known whether these functions are indeed one-way; but extensive research has so far failed to produce an efficient inverting algorithm for any of them.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The function *f* takes as inputs two prime numbers *p* and *q* in binary notation and returns their product.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] This function can be "easily" computed in *O*(*b*2) time, where *b* is the total number of bits of the inputs.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Inverting this function requires finding the factors of a given integer *N*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The best factoring algorithms known run in $O\left(\exp {\sqrt[{3}]{{\frac {64}{9}}b(\log b)^{2}}}\right)$ time, where b is the number of bits needed to represent *N*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] This function can be generalized by allowing *p* and *q* to range over a suitable set of semiprimes.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The **Rabin function**, or squaring modulo $N=pq$ , where p and q are primes is believed to be a collection of one-way functions.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] to denote squaring modulo N: a specific member of the **Rabin collection**.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] It can be shown that extracting square roots, i.e. inverting the Rabin function, is computationally equivalent to factoring N (in the sense of polynomial-time reduction).
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Hence it can be proven that the Rabin collection is one-way if and only if factoring is hard.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] This also holds for the special case in which p and q are of the same bit length.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The Rabin signature algorithm is based on the assumption that this Rabin function is one-way.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Modular exponentiation can be done in polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Inverting this function requires computing the discrete logarithm.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Currently there are several popular groups for which no algorithm to calculate the underlying discrete logarithm in polynomial time is known.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] These groups are all finite abelian groups and the general discrete logarithm problem can be described as thus.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Let *G* be a finite abelian group of cardinality *n*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Denote its group operation by multiplication.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Consider a primitive element *α* ∈ *G* and another element *β* ∈ *G*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The integer *k* that solves the equation *αk* = *β* is termed the **discrete logarithm** of *β* to the base *α*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Popular choices for the group *G* in discrete logarithm cryptography are the cyclic groups (**Z***p*)*×* (e.g.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] ElGamal encryption, Diffie–Hellman key exchange, and the Digital Signature Algorithm) and cyclic subgroups of elliptic curves over finite fields (*see* elliptic curve cryptography).
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] An elliptic curve is a set of pairs of elements of a field satisfying *y*2 = *x*3 + *ax* + *b*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The elements of the curve form a group under an operation called "point addition" (which is not the same as the addition operation of the field).
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Multiplication *kP* of a point *P* by an integer *k* (*i.e.*, a group action of the additive group of the integers) is defined as repeated addition of the point to itself.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] If *k* and *P* are known, it is easy to compute *R* = *kP*, but if only *R* and *P* are known, it is assumed to be hard to compute *k*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] There are a number of cryptographic hash functions that are fast to compute, such as SHA-256.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Some of the simpler versions have fallen to sophisticated analysis, but the strongest versions continue to offer fast, practical solutions for one-way computation.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Most of the theoretical support for the functions are more techniques for thwarting some of the previously successful attacks.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Other candidates for one-way functions include the hardness of the decoding of random linear codes, the hardness of certain lattice problems, and the subset sum problem (Naccache–Stern knapsack cryptosystem).
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] There is an explicit function *f* that has been proved to be one-way, if and only if one-way functions exist.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] In other words, if any function is one-way, then so is *f*.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Since this function was the first combinatorial complete one-way function to be demonstrated, it is known as the "universal one-way function".
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] The problem of finding a one-way function is thus reduced to proving—perhaps non-constructively—that one such function exists.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] There also exists a function that is one-way if polynomial-time bounded Kolmogorov complexity is mildly hard on average.
[src:average-case-complexity/one-way-function] Since the existence of one-way functions implies that polynomial-time bounded Kolmogorov complexity is mildly hard on average, the function is a universal one-way function.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] In computational complexity theory, a **planted clique** or **hidden clique** in an undirected graph is a clique formed from another graph by selecting a subset of vertices and adding edges between each pair of vertices in the subset.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The **planted clique problem** is the algorithmic problem of distinguishing random graphs from graphs that have a planted clique.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] This is a variation of the clique problem; it may be solved in quasi-polynomial time but is conjectured not to be solvable in polynomial time for intermediate values of the clique size.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The conjecture that no polynomial time solution exists is called the **planted clique conjecture**; it has been used as a computational hardness assumption.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] A clique in a graph is a subset of vertices, all of which are adjacent to each other.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] A planted clique is a clique created from another graph by adding edges between all pairs of a selected subset of vertices.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The planted clique problem can be formalized as a decision problem over a random distribution on graphs, parameterized by two numbers, n (the number of vertices), and k (the size of the clique).
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Decide whether or not to add a clique to the graph, with probability 1/2; if not, return the graph formed in step 1.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Choose randomly a subset of k of the n vertices and add an edge (if one is not already present) between each pair of the selected vertices.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The problem is then to determine algorithmically whether one of the graphs resulting from this process contains a clique of at least k vertices.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] There exists a function $f(n)\sim 2\log _{2}n$ such that asymptotically almost surely, the size of the largest clique in an n-vertex random graph is either $f(n)$ or $f(n)+1$ , and there exists some constant c such that the expected number of cliques of size $\geq f(n)-c$ converges to infinity.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Consequently, one should expect that the planting a clique of size $\sim 2\log _{2}n$ cannot be detected with high probability.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] By the central limit theorem, the vertex degrees of the random graph would be distributed close to a standard normal distribution with mean ${\frac {n}{2}}$ and standard deviation ${\frac {\sqrt {n}}{2}}$ .
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Consequently, when k is on the order of ${\sqrt {n}}$ it would create a detectable change in the shape of the distribution.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Namely, if you plot out the vertex degree distribution, it would look like a deformed bell curve.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] For sufficiently large values of the parameter k, the planted clique problem can be solved (with high probability) in polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Kučera (1995) observes that, when $k=\Omega ({\sqrt {n\log n}})$ then almost surely all vertices of the planted clique have higher degree than all vertices outside the clique, making the clique very easy to find.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] He describes a modification to the random process for generating planted clique instances, that makes the vertex degrees more uniform even for large values of k, but shows that despite this modification the planted clique may still be found quickly.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Select the k vertices whose coordinates in this eigenvector have the largest absolute values.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Return the set of vertices that are adjacent to at least 3/4 of the selected vertices.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] They show how to modify this technique so that it continues to work whenever k is at least proportional to some multiple of the square root of the number of vertices.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Large planted cliques can also be found using semidefinite programming.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] A combinatorial technique based on randomly sampling vertices can achieve the same bound on k and runs in linear time.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] It is also possible to solve the planted clique problem, regardless of the choice of k, in quasi-polynomial time.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] For each choice of S, test whether S is a clique.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Otherwise, find the set T of vertices that are adjacent to all vertices in S.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The running time of this algorithm is quasipolynomial, because there are quasipolynomially many choices of S to loop over.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] This method is guaranteed to try a set S that is a subset of the planted clique; with high probability, the set T will consist only of other members of the planted clique.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] There are two versions of the planted clique conjecture: one based on finding the clique (search) and one based on determining if a clique exists (decision).
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The search conjecture states that no polynomial time algorithm can find (with high probability) a clique of size k << $n^{0.5}$ in a random graph with n nodes and a hidden clique of size k .
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Suppose we are given two n node random graphs, exactly one of which has a planted clique, but we don't know which.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] On average, a random graph with a planted clique will have more edges than a purely random graph, since the act of planting a clique of size k is expected to add $\Theta (k^{2})$ edges.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Therefore, we can correctly determine which of the two graphs contains the planted clique with probability $1/2+\Theta (k^{2}/n)$ by simply counting the number of edges in each graph.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The decision planted clique conjecture states that this is essentially optimal: it postulates that no polynomial time algorithm can distinguish between the two graphs with probability higher than $1/2+\Theta (k^{2}/n)$ .
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] Hazan & Krauthgamer (2011) used the assumption that finding planted cliques is hard as a computational hardness assumption to prove that, if so, it is also hard to approximate the best Nash equilibrium in a two-player game.
[src:average-case-complexity/planted-clique] The planted clique conjecture has also been used as a hardness assumption to show the difficulty of property testing k-independence of random distributions, finding clusters in social networks, and machine learning.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] In theoretical computer science, **smoothed analysis** is a way of measuring the complexity of an algorithm.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Since its introduction in 2001, smoothed analysis has been used as a basis for considerable research, for problems ranging from mathematical programming, numerical analysis, machine learning, and data mining.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] It can give a more realistic analysis of the practical performance (e.g., running time, success rate, approximation quality) of the algorithm compared to analysis that uses worst-case or average-case scenarios.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Smoothed analysis is a hybrid of worst-case and average-case analyses that inherits advantages of both.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] It measures the expected performance of algorithms under slight random perturbations of worst-case inputs.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] If the smoothed complexity of an algorithm is low, then it is unlikely that the algorithm will take a long time to solve practical instances whose data are subject to slight noises and imprecisions.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Smoothed complexity results are strong probabilistic results, roughly stating that, in every large enough neighbourhood of the space of inputs, most inputs are easily solvable.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Thus, a low smoothed complexity means that the hardness of inputs is a "brittle" property.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Although worst-case complexity has been widely successful in explaining the practical performance of many algorithms, this style of analysis gives misleading results for a number of problems.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Worst-case complexity measures the time it takes to solve any input, although hard-to-solve inputs might never come up in practice.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] In such cases, the worst-case running time can be much worse than the observed running time in practice.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] For example, the worst-case complexity of solving a linear program using the simplex algorithm is exponential, although the observed number of steps in practice is roughly linear.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] The simplex algorithm is in fact much faster than the ellipsoid method in practice, although the latter has polynomial-time worst-case complexity.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Average-case analysis was first introduced to overcome the limitations of worst-case analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] However, the resulting average-case complexity depends heavily on the probability distribution that is chosen over the input.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] The actual inputs and distribution of inputs may be different in practice from the assumptions made during the analysis: a random input may be very unlike a typical input.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Because of this choice of data model, a theoretical average-case result might say little about practical performance of the algorithm.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Smoothed analysis generalizes both worst-case and average-case analysis and inherits strengths of both.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] It is intended to be much more general than average-case complexity, while still allowing low complexity bounds to be proven.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] ACM and the European Association for Theoretical Computer Science awarded the 2008 Gödel Prize to Daniel Spielman and Shanghua Teng for developing smoothed analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] The name Smoothed Analysis was coined by Alan Edelman.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] In 2010 Spielman received the Nevanlinna Prize for developing smoothed analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Spielman and Teng's JACM paper "Smoothed analysis of algorithms: Why the simplex algorithm usually takes polynomial time" was also one of the three winners of the 2009 Fulkerson Prize sponsored jointly by the Mathematical Programming Society (MPS) and the American Mathematical Society (AMS).
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] The simplex algorithm is a very efficient algorithm in practice, and it is one of the dominant algorithms for linear programming in practice.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] On practical problems, the number of steps taken by the algorithm is linear in the number of variables and constraints.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Yet in the theoretical worst case it takes exponentially many steps for most successfully analyzed pivot rules.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] This was one of the main motivations for developing smoothed analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] For the perturbation model, we assume that the input data is perturbed by noise from a Gaussian distribution.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] This bound holds for a specific pivot rule called the shadow vertex rule.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] The shadow vertex rule is slower than more commonly used pivot rules such as Dantzig's rule or the steepest edge rule but it has properties that make it very well-suited to probabilistic analysis.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] A number of local search algorithms have bad worst-case running times but perform well in practice.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] One example is the 2-opt heuristic for the traveling salesman problem.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] It can take exponentially many iterations until it finds a locally optimal solution, although in practice the running time is subquadratic in the number of vertices.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] The approximation ratio, which is the ratio between the length of the output of the algorithm and the length of the optimal solution, tends to be good in practice but can also be bad in the theoretical worst case.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] One class of problem instances can be given by n points in the box $[0,1]^{d}$ , where their pairwise distances come from a norm.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Already in two dimensions, the 2-opt heuristic might take exponentially many iterations until finding a local optimum.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] In this setting, one can analyze the perturbation model where the vertices $v_{1},\dots ,v_{n}$ are independently sampled according to probability distributions with probability density function $f_{1},\dots ,f_{n}:[0,1]^{d}\rightarrow [0,\theta ]$ .
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] For $\theta =1$ , the points are uniformly distributed.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] When $\theta >1$ is big, the adversary has more ability to increase the likelihood of hard problem instances.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] In this perturbation model, the expected number of iterations of the 2-opt heuristic, as well as the approximation ratios of resulting output, are bounded by polynomial functions of n and $\theta$ .
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Another local search algorithm for which smoothed analysis was successful is the k-means method.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Given n points in $[0,1]^{d}$ , it is NP-hard to find a good partition into clusters with small pairwise distances between points in the same cluster.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] Lloyd's algorithm is widely used and very fast in practice, although it can take $e^{\Omega (n)}$ iterations in the worst case to find a locally optimal solution.
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] However, assuming that the points have independent Gaussian distributions, each with expectation in $[0,1]^{d}$ and standard deviation $\sigma$ , the expected number of iterations of the algorithm is bounded by a polynomial in n , d and $\sigma$ .
[src:average-case-complexity/smoothed-analysis] There are problems that provably *cannot* be solved in smoothed polynomial time.
